node.text:
“Tương Bần (soya sauce) is a delicacy salty paste made from fermented soybeans. It is a popular dipping sauce for vegetables, Vietnamese-style spring rolls, and boiled meat. It is also used as a condiment for home cooks or restaurants. This can be found in many localities, but the most delicious one is made by locals in Ban Yen Nhan town, Hung Yen province.

The main ingredient of the sauce is soybean, sticky rice, and sea salt. The rice is washed, boiled, and left for a few days till it turns yellow with the fungus, and then it dries for a few more days. The fermented rice is then mixed with soybeans, salt, and water.

The mixture is poured into earthen or ceramic jars, which are covered tightly and dried in the sun for two to six months. Sunlight heats up the jars, contributing to advancing the speed of the process. During the drying period, artisans workers will stir the mixture every morning and noon for a few minutes so the sauce can be blended well together.” – Phuc Le
cc: @phucle1204
My Vietnam! Truly fall in love with this reel
